  "response": "Rainbows are curved because **raindrops are round.**\n\nHere's why:\n\n*   **Reflection and Refraction:** Rainbows are formed when sunlight enters a raindrop, is reflected off the back of the raindrop, and then refracted (bent) again as it exits the raindrop. This process separates the white light into its constituent colors.\n*   **Angle of Emission:** The most intense light emerges from the raindrops at an angle of approximately 42 degrees relative to the incoming sunlight.\n*   **Creating the Arc:** Imagine yourself as the observer and the sun is behind you. The raindrops that are reflecting and refracting the sunlight to your eyes at that 42-degree angle form a circle (or rather, a cone with your eye as the apex). Since the ground usually blocks the lower part of the circle, you typically see an arc. If you were in an airplane, you might see a full circle.\n*   **Earth's Curvature:** While the Earth is round, its curvature doesn't directly cause the rainbow's arc. The rainbow is primarily a consequence of the consistent way that light interacts with spherical raindrops.\n\nIn summary, the shape of the rainbow depends on how light travels through spherical raindrops.",
